{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17536008","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17536008"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:02:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:02:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15564"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15564","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15564"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.11,0.06,0.26,0.33]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8255"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61881"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8255","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8255"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15564"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47327"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1156"},{"type":"tags","id":"1181"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4978"},{"type":"tags","id":"5790"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19948"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41447"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43584"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61881","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61881"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 23-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of right-sided neck swelling and upper jaw pain. He reports pain and bleeding when brushing his teeth, particularly around his upper right back teeth. He denies fever, night sweats, or recent infections. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are several tender, mobile lymph nodes in the right anterior cervical chain measuring up to 2 cm. Intraoral examination reveals inflammation and erythema around a partially erupted right upper wisdom tooth with visible food debris. The surrounding gum tissue is tender to palpation. The remainder of the oral cavity appears healthy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral amoxicillin","Incision and drainage","Fine needle aspiration of lymph node","Immediate dental extraction","Chlorhexidine mouthwash"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features consistent with pericoronitis, which is inflammation of the soft tissue surrounding a partially erupted tooth, most commonly affecting wisdom teeth. The combination of localised pain, tender cervical lymphadenopathy, and inflammation around a partially erupted wisdom tooth is characteristic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChlorhexidine mouthwash\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial management, along with oral hygiene instruction and warm salt water rinses. This helps reduce bacterial load and inflammation in the affected area. The patient should be advised to pay particular attention to cleaning around the affected tooth, though carefully due to the tenderness. If there are ongoing symptoms or progression, referral to a dentist should be considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral amoxicillin\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated as first-line treatment in the absence of systemic symptoms or evidence of spreading infection. Antibiotics should be reserved for cases with facial swelling, trismus, or systemic symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate dental extraction\u003C/strong\u003E may ultimately be necessary but is not appropriate as initial management during the acute inflammatory phase. The inflammation should first be controlled with conservative measures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncision and drainage\u003C/strong\u003E would only be indicated if there was a localised abscess, which is not described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFine needle aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E of the lymph node would be unnecessary and inappropriate given the clear local cause for the lymphadenopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient should be advised to follow up with a dentist for definitive management, which may include extraction of the wisdom tooth once the acute inflammation has settled.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pericoronitis commonly presents with tender lymphadenopathy and upper jaw pain in young adults.","Initial management of pericoronitis includes chlorhexidine mouthwash and oral hygiene instruction.","Systemic antibiotics are only indicated if there are signs of spreading infection or systemic symptoms."],"references":["Schalch TO, Martimbianco AL, Goncalves ML, Motta LJ, Santos EM, Cecatto RB, Bussadori SK, Horliana AC. Interventions for early-stage pericoronitis: systematic review of randomized clinical trials. Antibiotics. 2022 Jan 8;11(1):71. Available online at ; https://www.mdpi.com/2079-6382/11/1/71","Timmerman A, Parashos P. Management of dental pain in primary care. Aust Prescr 2020;43:39\u201344. https://doi.org/10.18773/austprescr.2020.010. Available online at ; https://australianprescriber.tg.org.au/articles/management-of-dental-pain-in-primary-care.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47327"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15564"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47327","links":{"self":"